anti-templating cross-check:
  C13 lead: decision-architecture framing ("If you own a leasehold flat with 70-99
    years remaining, you have two statutory routes: extend the lease for a peppercorn-
    rent 990-year term under LRHUDA 1993 Chapter II, or join with neighbours to buy
    the freehold under Chapter I"). H2 architecture: two parallel statutory regimes +
    LFRA 2024 changes + premium-calculation by regime + SDLT by route + three worked
    examples + practical control/ground-rent/lender/disposal + decision-grid +
    CGT/IHT/ATED interactions + timeline + what-to-do.
  C14 lead: common-law doctrine framing ("Any extension of the term of a lease
    operates at common law as the surrender of the existing lease and the grant of a
    new lease in substitution (Friends Provident Life Office v British Railways Board
    [1996] 1 All ER 336)"). H2 architecture: common-law doctrine + s.43 + Sch 17A
    paras 9/13/15A + para 14 repeal + LRHUDA Chapter II application + LRA 1967
    application + voluntary application + worked overlap-relief + boundary cases +
    LBTT/LTT + non-surrender deemed-new-lease paras + HRAD + practical advice.
  C15 lead: name-collision disambiguation framing ("A 'deed of variation' in the lease
    context is entirely different from a 'deed of variation' in the inheritance
    context (IHTA 1984 s.142). This page covers the former..."). H2 architecture:
    s.43(3)(b) surrender treatment + s.43(3)(d) variation treatment + reverse premium
    framework + deemed surrender by operation of law + tenant's CGT (full + part
    disposal + Sch 8 wasting asset) + 4 worked examples + trigger/non-trigger boundary
    + LBTT/LTT + HRAD + practical advice.
  Three distinct H1/H2/voice/lead profiles, no templating drift detected across the
  three sister pages (which share the §31 HP anchor but cover decision-architecture,
  doctrinal-mechanic, and non-statutory-voluntary-variation scopes respectively).

cannibalisation discipline notes:
  C13 / C14 / C15 three-page split (all sharing §31 HP anchor):
    C13 = decision architecture (which route: extension or freehold acquisition).
          Audience: leaseholder weighing options.
    C14 = doctrinal mechanic (HOW the surrender-and-regrant doctrine drives SDLT).
          Audience: adviser running the SDLT computation on a statutory or voluntary
          extension.
    C15 = non-statutory voluntary variation / surrender framework (including reverse
          premium, deemed surrender, tenant CGT). Audience: commercial property
          solicitor / residential leasehold manager / portfolio landlord's tax adviser.
    Explicit body cross-links between all three pages. Explicit body cross-link from
    each to the existing sdlt-leasehold-extension-vs-fresh-purchase rate-mechanics
    page. Explicit body cross-link from each to the Archer M1-A-B2 Scottish LBTT case.
    Explicit body cross-link from C15 to the existing IHTA 1984 s.142 deed-of-variation
    page for the name-collision disambiguation. No content overlap on the substantive
    coverage sections; each page handles its scope with no cross-contamination.

